#We can see that the larger the enginesize, the higher the price of the car.
#Enginesize graph looks similar to the stroke and horsepower graphs, thus we can infer that the three of those are most likely tied together in some way and have a similar effect on the price of a vehicle, so a higher one of those equates to a higher price for the vehicle.
#The peak RPM graph is very scattered, there does not seem to be a strong correlation there so maybe it has nothing to do with the price of a car.
#We can see that the city mpg and highway mpg graphs are also similar looking, so they are probably also tied together with a similar effect of the price of the vehicle. We can see that the lower mpg a car gets (be it city or highway), the more expensive that vehicle tends to be.
#Compression ratio seems very random and has no correlation from the looks of it, so we can conclude that it does not have much of an effect on the price of a vehicle. Also we can see that most compression ratios fall between 8 and 10.
#The wheel base and bore ratio seem to have a strong positive correlation, so we can see that a higher one of those equates to a higher price for the vehicle.

#In conclusion, there are many factors that affect a vehicles price. We created many graphs above such as scatterplots and boxplots to see exactly how price is affected by various variables. It seems that some features have a larger affect on price than others.
#Some of the features that seem to have a larger increase in price include things like the car's weight, car's horsepower, and engine size, which were very strongly correlated with price up above (higher horsepower/ larger enginesize / heavier curb weight = higher price) and thus were good indicators to judge what the price of the vehicle would be.
#Other things such as mpg were the opposite, a better mpg (city or highway) meant a lower price for the vehicle in general. On the other hand, some variables seem to have very little to no effect on price, as we saw above that for compression ratio and peak rpm, there seemed to be no trend between that and the price of a vehicle, so it didn't matter what the values were for those.
#We also saw the engine type, cylinder type, fuel system, and drivewheel countplots to determine which one of these was the most common among vehicles and compared each one's categories (such as having rwd vs fwd for drivewheel) to the price to see if there could be any savings in production costs when deciding which one of those to add to the vehicle (which for drivewheel, we saw from the graph that fwd vehicle's were cheaper than rwd were, so to save costs we could maybe add fwd instead of rwd to the vehicle). With cylinder's, we saw that four cylinder vehicles were much cheaper than six cylinder ones were, so maybe adding four cylinder to a car would be better since then we could charge less for the car, or add a six cylinder if we want to charge more for the car. 
#The above dataframe of the model's coefficients was also a useful tool to guage which features had the greatest impact in the price of a vehicle if we were looking at a specific feature of the car, like for example if we wanted to see whether having four cylinders or six cylinders seemed to have a larger variability on the price of a vehicle, we can see from the dataframe that four cylinder seems to have a higher coefficient, so we can maybe be more flexible with the pricing for four cylinder cars as opposed to six cylinder ones since there is more room to work with when moving from one unit to another.
